hews to wear a Depend undergarment in ad|last=Sorgi|first=Jay|date=March 29, 2012|work=WTMJ-620|accessdate=May 14, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130729024823/http://www.620wtmj.com/news/local/144873065.html|archive-date=July 29, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Matthews and his wife have three children together.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Grott |first1=Connor |title=Los Angeles Rams ink former Green Bay Packers LB Clay Matthews |url=https://www.upi.com/Los-Angeles-Rams-ink-former-Green-Bay-Packers-LB-Clay-Matthews/1891553046531/ |website=UPI.com |accessdate=March 20, 2019 |date=March 19, 2019 |quote=The longtime Packers pass rusher had more lucrative offers on the table, according to the NFL Network, but he wanted to remain close to home after the birth of his third child.}}</ref>\n\n==Non-sports media appearances==\nMatthews made an appearance on the February 9, 2011 of ''[[WWE]] [[WWE Smackdown|Smackdown]]'',<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.wwe.com/inside/news/claymatthewsinterview |title= Clay Matthews \u2013 next WWE Superstar? | website= WWE.com| location= Green Bay, Wisconsin| access-date= September 10, 2013}}</ref> when he ran down to the ring to assist in [[Edge (wrestler)|Edge's]] World Heavyweight Championship match against [[Dolph Ziggler]] as a backup referee, as [[Vickie Guerrero]] was the original special referee for that match. Guerrero injured her ankle ([[kayfabe]]) after trying to spear Edge, and he won the match and the championship after spearing Ziggler twice, while she was being attended to at ringside for her injury. Shortly after the second spear, Matthews ran down to the ring to make the three-count and give Edge the win.<ref>{{YouTube|g5RTtoxbjUY|Edge vs Dolph Ziggler (World Heavyweight Championship Match) 2/11/11}}. Cesar Garcia. Retrieved September 10, 2013</ref> This episode took place in Green Bay, the same week the Green Bay Packers won the [[Super Bowl XLV]] after [[WWE]] invited the winning team to the show that is taking place in their hometown.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://scores.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=310206009| title=Aaron Rodgers tosses 3 TD passes as Packers drop Steelers to win Super Bowl XLV| date= February 7, 2011| location= Arlington, Texas| publisher= ESPN| access-date= February 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\nMatthews and his former Packers teammates [[Josh Sitton]], [[David Bakhtiari]], [[T. J. Lang]], and [[Don Barclay (American football)|Don Barclay]] had cameo appearances in the film ''[[Pitch Perfect 2]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rich|first1=Katey|title=How the Green Bay Packers Cameo in Pitch Perfect 2 Happened|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/05/pitch-perfect-2-kay-cannon|website=vanityfair.com|accessdate=March 10, 2018|date=May 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://usctrojans.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/matthews_clay00.html USC bio]\n* [http://www.packers.com/team/roster/Clay-Matthews/c908095d-15b6-452b-96f9-26d9c276d819 Green Bay Packers bio]\n* [https://www.therams.com/team/players-roster/clay-matthews/ Los Angeles Rams bio]\n* [http://espn.go.com/nfl/player/_/id/12438/clay-matthews ESPN profile]\n\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{2009 NFL Draft}}\n{{PackersFirstPick}}\n{{Packers2009DraftPicks}}\n{{Dick Butkus Award (professional)}}\n{{Super Bowl XLV}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Matthews, Clay 03}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football linebackers]]\n[[Category:Green Bay Packers players]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Rams players]]\n[[Category:Matthews football family]]\n[[Category:National Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:People from Agoura Hills, California]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from California]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Los Angeles County, California]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl champions]]\n[[Category:Unconferenced Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:USC Trojans football players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football outside linebacker}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name = Clay Matthews III\n| image = Clay Matthews - San Francisco vs Green Bay 2012.jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = Matthews III with the Green Bay Packers in 2012\n| number = \n| current_team = Free agent\n| position = [[Outside linebacker]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1986|05|14}}\n| birth_place = [[Los Angeles, California]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 3\n| weight_lbs = 255\n| high_school = [[Agoura High School|Agoura]]<br />([[Agoura Hills, California]])\n| college = [[USC Trojans football|USC]]\n| draftyear = 2009\n| draftround = 1\n| draftpick = 26\n| pastteams =\n* [[Green Bay Packers]] ({{NFL Year|2009}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2018}})\n* [[Los Angeles Rams]] ({{NFL Year|2019}})\n| status = \n| highlights =\n* [[Super Bowl]] champion ([[Super Bowl XLV|XLV]])\n* 6\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2010 Pro Bowl|2009]]\u2013[[2013 Pro Bowl|2012]], [[2015 Pro Bowl|2014]], [[2016 Pro Bowl|2015]])\n* First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2010 All-Pro Team|2010]])\n* 2\u00d7 Second-team All-Pro ([[2012 All-Pro Team|2012]], [[2014 All-Pro Team|2014]])\n* [[Pro Football Writers Association NFL Defensive Player of the Year|PFWA NFL Defensive Player of the Year]] (2010)\n* [[Butkus Award]] (2010)\n* 3\u00d7 [[Pac-12 Conference|Pac-10 champion]] (2006\u20132008)\n| statweek = \n| statseason = 2019\n| statlabel1 = [[Tackle (football move)|Total tackles]]\n| statvalue1 = 519\n| statlabel2 = [[Quarterback sack|Sacks]]\n| statvalue2 = 91.5\n| statlabel3 = [[Pass deflected|Pass deflections]]\n| statvalue3 = 43\n| statlabel4 = [[Interception]]s\n| statvalue4 = 6\n| statlabel5 = [[Fumble|Forced fumbles]]\n| statvalue5 = 17\n| statlabel6 = [[Touchdown|Defensive touchdowns]]\n| statvalue6 = 3\n| nflnew = claymatthews/80431\n| pfr = MattCl99\n}}\n'''William Clay Matthews III''' (born May 14, 1986) is an [[American football]] [[outside linebacker]] who is a [[free agent]]. After attending [[Agoura High School]] in [[Agoura Hills, California]], Matthews was a [[walk-on (sports)|walk-on]] [[student athlete]] at the [[University of Southern California]] for the [[USC Trojans football]] team under head coach [[Pete Carroll]]. At USC, Matthews was a standout [[special-teams]] player, winning three consecutive Special Teams Player of the Year awards from 2006 to 2008. He also played reserve outside linebacker during those years before moving into a starting role his senior season. During his college career, he was a part of three [[Pac-12 Conference|Pac-10 Championship]] teams.\n \nMatthews was considered a top prospect for the [[2009 NFL Draft]]. He was ultimately selected by the [[Green Bay Packers]] in the first round of the draft (26th overall) after the team traded up to make the selection. In his rookie year, Matthews recorded 10 [[quarterback sacks|sacks]] while playing outside linebacker. He topped that total in 2010 with 13.5 sacks, helping the Packers to their [[Super Bowl XLV]] victory against the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]]. Matthews continued his role as a leading pass rusher, recording at least six sacks in the first nine seasons he played. He also has showed his athleticism and abilities by playing both [[inside linebacker|inside]] and [[outside linebacker]] during the [[2014 Green Bay Packers season|2014]] and [[2015 Green Bay Packers season|2015]] seasons.\n\nA member of the [[Matthews family]] of football players, he is the son of former NFL linebacker [[Clay Matthews Jr.]] and nephew of [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] offensive lineman [[Bruce Matthews (American football)|Bruce Matthews]].\n\n==Early life==\nMatthews was born in Los Angeles, California, the son of Leslie and [[Clay Matthews Jr.]], a professional [[American football|football]] player. The family has a history of professional football players. Matthews's grandfather was [[Clay Matthews Sr.]] His brother is linebacker [[Casey Matthews]], and his uncle is [[Bruce Matthews (American football)|Bruce Matthews]]. Both brothers were [[All-American]]s in their time in college. He also has cousins involved in football: [[Kevin Matthews (American football)|Kevin Matthews]], [[Jake Matthews (American football)|Jake Matthews]], and Mike Matthews.\n\n==High school career==\nMatthews attended Agoura High School in Agoura Hills, California, where he played for the Agoura Chargers [[high school football]] team. Physically, Matthews was a [[late bloomer]]. His father was the team's [[defensive coordinator]], but declined to start his son because he was physically undersized. Matthews began developing physically in his senior season, but only garnered interest from Division I [[Division I (NCAA)#Football Championship Subdivision|FCS]] schools and local [[community colleges]].<ref name=\"LAT092308\">{{Citation| last = Klein| first = Gary| title = Clay's feat: walk on, hold off, move up| newspaper = [[Los Angeles Times]]| date = September 23, 2008| accessdate = July 12, 2016 | url = https://articles.latimes.com/2008/sep/23/sports/sp-usc23}}</ref> He has described his own recruiting status out of high school as \"not applicable.\"<ref name=\"NYT110208\">{{Cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/nfcwest/post/_/id/35956/power-rankings-top-10-nfl-linebackers |title=Power Rankings: Top 10 NFL linebackers |work=espn |date=November 2, 2008 |accessdate=December 4, 2012 }}</ref> Like his father and uncle, Matthews opted to attend the [[University of Southern California]] with hopes of becoming a [[Walk-on (sports)|walk-on]] for the Trojans football team.\n\n==College career==\n[[File:2007-1020-ClayMatthewsIII.jpg|thumb|alt=Matthews during his 2007 season at USC|A college-age picture of Clay Matthews III, standing in a crowd of USC fans]]\n\nMatthews attended the University of Southern California and played for the Trojans from 2004 to 2008 under [[head coach]] [[Pete Carroll]]. Though he was the son of an All-Pro NFL linebacker, he entered USC as an unheralded, walk-on [[student athlete]]. During his first season, USC's [[2004 USC Trojans football team|2004 BCS National Championship]], he played only on the [[scout team]] and turned down several playing opportunities during [[garbage time]] during the fourth quarters of games to preserve his [[Redshirt (college sports)|redshirt]] status and remaining seasons of NCAA eligibility. He remained a nonathletic scholarship (a \"walk on\") reserve linebacker during the [[2005 USC Trojans football team|2005 season]], and played mainly on [[special teams]]. He was granted full [[athletic scholarship]] status at the beginning of the [[2006 USC Trojans football team|2006 season]]. Matthews continued to play reserve linebacker in the 2006 and [[2007 USC Trojans football team|2007 season]]s, and made two starts in 2007 in place of injured teammate [[Brian Cushing]].<ref name=\"LAT092308\"/> He was awarded USC's Co-Special Teams Player of the Year in 2006 and 2007 and blocked two field goals in the latter season.<ref name=WeAreSC050408>{{cite web |first=Erik |last=McKinney |url=http://wearesc.com/news/story.php?article=1011 |title=A Spot for Clay |website=WeAreSC.com |date=May 4, 2008 |access-date=January 29, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430081520/http://wearesc.com/news/story.php?article=1011 |archivedate=April 30, 2009}}</ref>\n\nDuring the off season, Matthews committed to weight training and conditioning programs to gain size and improve his performance level and stamina. At the beginning of the [[2008 USC Trojans football team|2008 season]], defensive coordinator [[Nick Holt]], Carroll, and Norton decided to try using Matthews in a hybrid \"elephant\" position, where Matthews would stand in the position of [[defensive end]], but use the speed and tactics of a linebacker; the coaches had used Cushing in the position in a similar manner in 2006.<ref name=\"LAT092308\"/> The experiment was successful, as Matthews recorded 4.5 sacks while playing alongside his other [[NFL]]-bound teammates Brian Cushing, [[Rey Maualuga]], and [[Kaluka Maiava]]. Furthermore, Matthews continued his spectacular special-teams play and was awarded USC's Co-Special Teams Player of the Year in 2008, making him the only player in USC history to be awarded three consecutive Special Teams Player of the Year awards. Matthews was a participant in the 2009 [[Senior Bowl]] and was considered a top prospect for the [[2009 NFL Draft]].<ref name=SN012109>{{cite news|first=Albert |last=Breer |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/yourturn/viewtopic.php?t=509434 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090126202454/http://www.sportingnews.com/yourturn/viewtopic.php?t=509434 |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 26, 2009 |title=USC just might be the true location of Linebacker U |work=[[Sporting News]] |date=January 21, 2009 |access-date=January 29, 2009}}</ref>\n\nMatthews was one of 12 senior USC football players, including the four linebackers Cushing, Maiava, Matthews, and Maualuga, attending the by-invitation-only 2009 [[NFL Scouting Combine]].<ref name=ESPN020209>{{cite news |first=Ted |last=Miller |url=http://myespn.go.com/blogs/pac10/0-7-1/Pac-10-NFL-combine-invitees.html |title=Pac-10 NFL combine invitees |website=ESPN.com |date=February 2, 2009 |access-date=February 2, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210115022/http://myespn.go.com/blogs/pac10/0-7-1/Pac-10-NFL-combine-invitees.html |archivedate=February 10, 2009}}</ref> Matthews, alongside fellow USC linebackers Maualuga and Cushing, was featured on the cover of ''Sports Illustrated''{{'}}s 2009 ''NFL Draft Preview'' magazine, as all three were regarded as potential first-round selections.<ref name=LAT042109>{{cite news| last=Klein | first= Gary| url= http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/sports_blog/2009/04/uscs-maualuga-cushing-and-matthews-grace-sports-illustrated-cover.html |title= USC's Maualuga, Kushing and Matthews grace ''Sports Illustrated'' cover| newspaper=LATimes.com| date= April 21, 2009| access-date= April 26, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n{{nfl predraft\n| height ft = 6\n| height in = 3\u215b\n| weight = 240\n| dash = 4.67\n| ten split = 1.49\n| twenty split = 2.71\n| shuttle = 4.18\n| cone drill = 6.90\n| vertical = 35\u00bd\n| broad ft = 10\n| broad in = 1\n| bench = 23\n| wonderlic = 26\n| note = All values from [[NFL Combine]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/clay-matthews?id=80431 |title = NFL Events: Combine Player Profiles - Clay Matthews}}</ref><ref>http://www.draftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=57020&draftyear=2009&genpos=olb</ref>\n}}\n\n===Green Bay Packers===\nOn August 7, 2008, the [[Green Bay Packers]] traded [[Brett Favre]] to the [[New York Jets]] for what would become the Jets' third-round draft pick (83rd overall) in the [[2009 NFL Draft]].\n\nOn draft day, April 25, 2009, the Packers traded their second-round pick (41st overall, [[Darius Butler]]), their third-round pick (73rd overall, [[Derek Cox]], [[Jacksonville Jaguars]]), and the 83rd overall pick acquired for Favre ([[Brandon Tate]]) to the [[New England Patriots]] for a first-round pick (26th overall) and a fifth-round pick (162nd overall, [[Jamon Meredith]]) in that year's draft.\n\nThe Packers used the first-round pick obtained from the Patriots to acquire Matthews with the 26th overall selection in the 2009 NFL Draft.\n\n[[Kevin Greene (American football)|Kevin Greene]], the former All-Pro linebacker who is third on the all-time sack list with 160 (most ever by a linebacker), was hired by [[Dom Capers]] in 2009 to coach the outside linebacker position. He saw a lot of himself in Matthews, but feared the Packers would not be able to draft him. Analysts were shocked when the Packers traded their second- and two third-round draft picks to the New England Patriots to secure Matthews and the fifth-round selection.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/draft/story/11667443| title= Prisco's Live Draft Analysis| first= Pete |last= Prisco | website=CBSSports.com| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090428210049/http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/draft/story/11667443| archivedate= April 28, 2009 | url-status=dead| date= April 26, 2009| access-date= August 27, 2016}}</ref> Analysts did not believe Matthews to be a first-round draft prospect due to his limited playing experience at USC (only starting the final ten games of his senior season.) Greene later stated that Matthews has a \"set of skills that I have not seen in an outside linebacker. Clay has a set of skills that I didn't have. He has another gear I didn't have. He's better than Kevin Greene was.\"<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.espnwisconsin.com/common/more.php?m=15&r=18&item_id=887| website= ESPNWisconsin.com| title= 'He's going to be a great one'| first= Jason| last= Wilde| location= Green Bay, Wisconsin| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140202142646/http://www.espnwisconsin.com/common/more.php?m=15&r=18&item_id=887| archivedate= February 2, 2014| url-status=dead| date= | access-date= August 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Clay Matthews III 1.jpg|thumb|upright|Matthews on the field for the Packers in August 2011|alt=A picture of Clay Matthews III on the filed in uniform adjusting his chin strap]]\n\n====2009 season====\nMatthews scored his first career touchdown during a ''[[Monday Night Football]]'' game on October 5, 2009 against the [[2009 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]]; Matthews stripped the ball from running back [[Adrian Peterson]] and ran the ball back for a touchdown.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2009100500/2009/REG4/packers@vikings/analyze/box-score#analyze-channels:cat-post-playbyplay |title=NFL Game Center: Green Bay Packers at Minnesota Vikings \u2013 2009 Week 4 |publisher=Nfl.com |date= |accessdate=December 22, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101114093800/http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2009100500/2009/REG4/packers@vikings/analyze/box-score#analyze-channels:cat-post-playbyplay |archive-date=November 14, 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/06/sports/football/06vikings.html |title=Finally Facing the Packers, Favre Delivers a Gem |first=Pat |last=Borzi |newspaper= The New York Times |date=October 6, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn Week 10 against the [[2009 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]], Matthews had another outstanding game: recording one tackle, recovering two fumbles forced by cornerback [[Charles Woodson]], and sacking Dallas quarterback [[Tony Romo]] to make him a nominee again for the Pepsi NFL Rookie of the Week. For the second time in as many nominations, he was voted Rookie of the Week for week 10.<ref name= \"pepsi rookie\"/>\n\nIn Week 12 against the [[2009 Detroit Lions season|Detroit Lions]], he made three tackles, assisted on two more, and sacked [[Daunte Culpepper]] twice. He was nominated for and won the [[Pepsi NFL Rookie of the Week]] award for his performance.<ref name=\"pepsi rookie\">{{cite web| url= http://www.nfl.com/partner?partnerType=rookies&season=2009&seasonType=REG&week=10 |date= November 20, 2009 | title= Matthews named Pepsi NFL Rookie of the Week | website= NFL.com | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091203174416/http://www.nfl.com/partner?partnerType=rookies&season=2009&seasonType=REG&week=10| archivedate= December 3, 2009| url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nMatthews had arguably the best game in his young career in Week 13 when he was awarded the NFC Defensive Player of the Week award. Matthews had six tackles, two sacks and a forced fumble in the Packers' 27\u201314 win over the [[2009 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]].<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.packers.com/news/releases/2009/12/09/3/?| url-status=dead| website= packers.com| title= LB Clay Matthews Named NFC Defensive Player Of Week 13| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091213040803/http://www.packers.com/news/releases/2009/12/09/3/| archivedate= December 13, 2009| date= December 9, 2009| accessdate= August 27, 2016| df= mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn the Packers' December 13, 2009, contest against the [[2009 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]] at [[Soldier Field]], Matthews recorded his eighth sack of the season which put him into a three-way tie with former Packers [[Tim Harris (linebacker)|Tim Harris]] and [[Vonnie Holiday]] for the team record of most sacks in a rookie season (1982\u2013present).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.packers.com/history/record_book/individual_records/defense/ |title=Packers Record Book |accessdate=May 14, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081227202256/http://www.packers.com/history/record_book/individual_records/defense/ |archivedate=December 27, 2008 }}</ref> The following week, Matthews recorded two more sacks vs the [[2009 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]] to claim the rookie record.<ref>{{cite web |title=Packers vs Steelers Gamecenter |url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2009122006/2009/REG15/packers@steelers/analyze/box-score |accessdate=May 14, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100409082023/http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2009122006/2009/REG15/packers%40steelers/analyze/box-score |archivedate=April 9, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=2009 Gamelogs|url=http://www.nfl.com/players/claymatthews/gamelogs?id=MAT538690&season=2009 |accessdate=May 14, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125143433/http://www.nfl.com/players/claymatthews/gamelogs?id=MAT538690 |archivedate=November 25, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nHe was added to the [[2010 Pro Bowl]] NFC squad, replacing [[Lance Briggs]]. He was the first Packers' rookie to earn a Pro Bowl selection since wide receiver [[James Lofton]] in 1978.\n\nMatthews recorded 51 tackles, 10 sacks, seven pass deflections, three fumble recoveries, and a forced fumble in his rookie season. He played in all 16 games, starting at ROLB in 13 of them. He led the Packers in QB pressures, with 45.5. He finished third for the NFL Defensive Rookie of the Year, losing to his former USC teammate Brian Cushing. He was named NFC Defensive Rookie of the Year and set the Packer record for most sacks in a season by a rookie, with 10.0.\n\n[[File:2012 Packers vs Giants - Clay Matthews.jpg|thumb|upright|Matthews during the January 15, 2012 game against the [[New York Giants]]|alt=A photo of Clay Matthews III in uniform on the field waiting for the play to begin]]\n\n====2010 season====\nMatthews took a different approach to the game in the 2010 season. After seeing him double-teamed and constantly chipped by running backs in the NFC wild card game against the [[2010 Arizona Cardinals season|Arizona Cardinals]], Dom Capers decided to move him around the field. Matthews eventually ended up playing mostly at LOLB, but he would roam around the field, playing also at the ROLB position and sometimes in the middle. He finished the season with 60 tackles, 13.5 sacks (fourth in the league), four pass deflections, two forced fumbles, and an interception through 15 games in 2010. He became the first Packer to record six sacks in the first two games of the season and had 8.5 sacks in the first five weeks, but slowed down the latter part of the season (five sacks in the last 10 games due to a stress fracture in his lower leg). Matthews was named to the [[2011 Pro Bowl]] NFC roster for the second straight year and was named to the All-Pro team for the first time in his career. Matthews was awarded with the NFL's defensive player of the month award for September after recording six sacks in the first two weeks of the 2010 season. Matthews recorded a career-high 55.0 quarterback pressures. He was named SN-NFL Defensive Player of the Year and NFC Defensive Player of the Year, and won the [[Butkus Award]]. He finished a close second (17 votes to 15) to [[Troy Polamalu]] in the [[AP NFL Defensive Player of the Year]] voting, notable in that both led their defenses to [[Super Bowl XLV]].\n\nHe set the Packers' record for most sacks in a single postseason with 3.5. In the Super Bowl, won by the Packers over the [[2010 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]], he recorded three tackles, a pass deflection, and a game-changing forced fumble. On the first play of the fourth quarter with the Steelers driving to take the lead with the score 21\u201317 in favor of Green Bay and the ball on the Packer 33 yard line, he tackled Steelers running back [[Rashard Mendenhall]], who fumbled the ball, recovered by [[Desmond Bishop]]. The Packers never lost the lead, winning their fourth [[Super Bowl]] title and first since [[Super Bowl XXXI]], 31\u201325.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201102060pit.htm |title=Super Bowl XLV \u2013 Pittsburgh Steelers vs. Green Bay Packers \u2013 February 6th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=December 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2011 season====\nMatthews finished the 2011 season with 50 tackles, and a career low six sacks despite playing 15 of the 16 games. He led the Packers in quarterback pressures for the third straight season, with 53.5. Although some of his numbers plummeted from the previous season, he improved in other aspects of his game. He recorded a career-high three interceptions, nine pass deflections, and three forced fumbles. He also recorded his third career defensive touchdown by picking off [[Eli Manning]] for a pick-six. Matthews played almost exclusively at the LOLB position, not roaming around the field like he did the previous season due to the struggling defense. Matthews did not play a single snap at the ROLB position until Week 11 and finished the entire season with only seven rushes from the ROLB spot. Matthews claimed he had his best overall season despite the low numbers. The Packers struggled to find pass pressure from the side opposite of Matthews and the loss of defensive end [[Cullen Jenkins]] due to [[free agent|free agency]] and safety [[Nick Collins]] due to a career-ending neck injury, placed the Packers last in total defense despite leading the league in interceptions, with 31. Linebacker coach Kevin Greene stated that he has never seen a pass rusher get double teamed as much as Clay had that season. The defensive line struggled, finishing the season with six total sacks after recording 18 the year before. Matthews was named to his third-straight Pro Bowl as a starter. Prior to the 2011 season, Matthews was named the second-best pass rusher (second only to [[DeMarcus Ware]]) and the fourth-best linebacker in the league by ESPN (behind [[Patrick Willis]], [[James Harrison (American football)|James Harrison]], and Ware).\n\n====2012 season====\nHeading into the 2012 season, the defense needed to improve. Finishing with the 32nd-ranked defense in the NFL was described by Matthews as \"unacceptable.\" The Packers picked six straight defensive players in the draft, including Matthews's former teammate, [[Nick Perry (American football)|Nick Perry]], out of USC. Because of Perry's larger size (10 pounds heavier) and not being accustomed to playing pass coverage, he was put at the LOLB position, and Matthews was moved back to the ROLB position he played at in his rookie year. The Packers hoped that by drafting Perry, as well as [[Michigan State Spartans football|Michigan State]] DE [[Jerel Worthy]] and [[Iowa Hawkeyes football|Iowa]] DE [[Mike Daniels (American football)|Mike Daniels]], opposing teams would no longer be able to consistently double-team Matthews, allowing pressure to open up on all sides.\n\n[[File:2012 Packers vs Giants - Clay Matthews 2.jpg|thumb|upright|Matthews playing against the [[New York Giants]] in 2012|alt=A picture of Clay Matthews in uniform on the field with his hands in the area, presumably to pump up the home-team crowd]]\n\nPrior to the 2012 season, ''[[Sporting News]]'' ranked Matthews as the second-best outside linebacker in the league, only behind Cowboys' star [[DeMarcus Ware]]. Matthews started out the season with a bang. He recorded 2.5 sacks in the 30\u201322 season opener loss to the eventual NFC champion [[2012 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]] and then posted a career-high 3.5 sacks against the [[2012 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]] on Thursday night. Matthews became one of only six players in NFL history to record six or more sacks in the first two games of the season, and is the only player ever to do it twice. Entering Week 9 against the [[2012 Arizona Cardinals season|Arizona Cardinals]], he was second in the league in sacks with nine. Matthews had to leave the game in the second half after his left hamstring started to tighten up. He was eventually ruled out for weeks 11 through 13. After missing four straight games with the hamstring injury, Matthews recorded six tackles, two sacks, and a pass deflection in a 21\u201313 victory over the Chicago Bears. This victory crowned the Packers as [[NFC North]] champions for the second year in a row. Matthews totaled three tackles and a sack in a 37\u201334 season ending loss to the [[2012 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]]. He finished the season with 43 tackles, 13.0 sacks (fifth in the league), two passes defended, and a forced fumble. Matthews was selected to his fourth straight Pro Bowl, but dropped out due to injury, and was named to the All-Pro team for the second time.\n\nIn the off-season, Matthews became the highest-paid linebacker in NFL history when the Packers and he made a deal worth $66 million over the next five seasons.\n\n====2013 season====\nPlaying in only 11 games during the 2013 season, Matthews recorded 41 tackles (26 solo), a team-high 7.5 sacks, and three forced fumbles. During the Packers' Week 5 matchup with the Detroit Lions on October 6, 2013, Matthews broke his right thumb and missed the next four games. On November 10, in a game at home against the [[2013 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]], he returned to the playing field, donning a large \"club\" cast over his entire right hand. Without the ability to use his fingers to grab or apply pressure or leverage, Matthews was left to be fairly ineffective during this game.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.packers.com/news/clay-matthews-is-done-with-the-club-11836701| website= Packers.com| title= Clay Matthews is done with the club| date= November 14, 2013| first= Mike |last= Spofford| access-date= August 27, 2016}}</ref> The following week, he returned to the field with a less restrictive device that allowed his fingers to remain free. The device seemed to improve his performance the following week. After completing only two tackles (one solo) with no sacks, stuffs, hits, or hurries on the quarterback against the Philadelphia Eagles, in the Packers' Week 11 match-up against the [[2013 New York Giants season|New York Giants]] the following week, Matthews had four tackles, including a sack and stuff with the less restrictive device.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://espn.go.com/nfl/player/gamelog/_/id/12438/clay-matthews| title= Clay Matthews Game-by-Game Stats| publisher= ESPN| date= | access-date= August 27, 2016}}</ref> After the Giants game, Matthews went on to accumulate 4.5 more sacks and 17 tackles (10 solo) over the next five weeks. In Week 16, during the second to last game of the regular season against the [[2013 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]], Matthews refractured his thumb and was out for the remainder of the season.\n\n====2014 season====\nPrior to the 2014 season, the Packers signed veteran free agent [[Julius Peppers]] to bring an additional pass rush to help Matthews. After a Week 8 loss to the [[2014 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]], where the Packers defense gave up almost 500 yards of offense, including 172 yards rushing from Mark Ingram, Packers defensive coordinator Dom Capers and head coach Mike McCarthy decided to alter Matthews's position, alternating him between outside linebacker and middle linebacker during games, depending on the play call. The move paid huge dividends for both Matthews and the Packers defense, as the defense improved drastically over the final eight games of the season. After spending the first half of the season ranked near the bottom in the league in defense, the Packers finished the season ranked a respectable 14th in the NFL in total defense. Matthews's sack numbers also increased in the second half of the season. After only getting 2.5 sacks in the first eight games, Matthews had 8.5 sacks in the final eight games, including back-to-back two-sack games against the [[2014 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]] and [[2014 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]]. Matthews finished the season with 11 sacks, 9 passes defended, one interception (his first since 2011), and two forced fumbles. For the first time in his NFL career, Matthews started every game during the regular season.\n\n====2015 season====\n[[File:Clay Matthews entering the stadium Cropped.jpg|thumb|Matthews entering [[Lambeau Field]] before a game in October 2015]]\nMatthews helped lead his team to the NFC Divisional Round playoff game against the [[2015 Arizona Cardinals season|Arizona Cardinals]], a game that it lost 26\u201320 in overtime. Matthews made comments that the Packers should have touched the ball in overtime and \"go to college rules\".<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2016/01/17/green-bay-packers-arizona-cardinals-clay-matthews/78926646/| title= Clay Matthews says NFL should 'go to college rules' after Packers don't touch ball in OT| first= Tom |last= Pelissero| newspaper= [[USA Today]]| date= January 17, 2016| access-date= August 27, 2016}}</ref> He was ranked 57th on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2016]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2016/0ap3000000666118/Top-100-Players-of-2016-No-57-Clay-Matthews|title='Top 100 Players of 2016': No. 57 Clay Matthews|website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\nMatthews was among the athletes indicated in ''[[The Dark Side: Secrets of the Sports Dopers]]'', an [[Al Jazeera]] [[documentary film|documentary]] on illegal [[performance-enhancing drugs]] use.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wJRPxmTuxoI| website= YouTube| publisher= [[Al Jazeera]]| title= Al Jazeera Investigates \u2013 The Dark Side: Secrets of the Sports Dopers| date= December 26, 2015| accessdate= August 27, 2016}}</ref> (In August 2016, after an investigation, the NFL cleared Matthews and two other of its players of wrongdoing, citing \"no credible evidence.\"<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2016/08/31/james-harrison-clay-mathhews-julius-peppers-al-jazeera-america/89658834/| title= NFL clears James Harrison, Clay Matthews, Julius Peppers in PED probe| work= [[USA Today]] | first= Tom |last= Pelissero| date= August 31, 2016| access-date= September 2, 2016}}</ref>)\n\nEvery Friday during the football season, Matthews appears on Wisconsin's ''Afternoon News'' with John Mercure on Newsradio 620 [[WTMJ (AM)|WTMJ]] and discusses football.\n\n====2016 season====\nIn the 2016 season, Matthews appeared in 12 games and started nine. He recorded 24 tackles, of which 20 were solo, five sacks, and one forced fumble. Despite posting a career-low in tackles and sacks, Matthews was ranked 82nd by his peers on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2017]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2017/0ap3000000805769/Top-100-Players-of-2017-No-82-Clay-Matthews|title='Top 100 Players of 2017': No. 82 Clay Matthews|website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n====2017 season====\nOn September 28, 2017, during the Week 4 game against the [[2017 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]], Matthews became the Packers' all-time sacks leader when he sacked the Bears' quarterback [[Mike Glennon]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Williams|first1=Charean|title=Clay Matthews becomes Packers' all-time sacks leader|url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2017/09/28/clay-matthews-becomes-packers-all-time-sacks-leader/|website=ProFootballTalk|accessdate=September 29, 2017|date=September 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2018 season====\nOn June 2, 2018, Matthews, who was pitching to Packers offensive lineman [[Lucas Patrick]] in the off-season Green & Gold Charity Softball Game, had a ball hit directly back to him. The line drive resulted in a broken nose for Matthews; surgery followed the incident.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shook |first1=Nick |title=Clay Matthews suffers broken nose in softball game |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000935442/article/clay-matthews-suffers-broken-nose-in-softball-game |website=NFL.com |accessdate=November 26, 2018 |date=June 2, 2018}}</ref> During the Packers' training camp for 2018, Matthews decided to wear a visor to add additional protection for his rhinoplasty.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Demovsky |first1=Rob |title=Packers LB Clay Matthews wearing visor on helmet to protect nose broken in softball game |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/24219425/clay-matthews-green-bay-packers-wearing-visor-protect-previously-broken-nose |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=November 26, 2018 |date=July 29, 2018}}</ref> During Week 2 against the [[2018 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]], Matthews was called for a controversial [[roughing the passer]] penalty that nullified an interception with 1:37 left in the fourth quarter. The game ended in a 29\u201329 tie.<ref>{{cite web |title=Clay Matthews III not fined for roughing the passer penalty |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/24754958/green-bay-packers-lb-clay-matthews-not-fined-roughing-passer-penalty |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=September 21, 2018|date=September 21, 2018 }}</ref> During Week 3 against the [[2018 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]], Matthews was again called for roughing the passer, becoming the first player to commit three roughing-the-passer penalties in the first three games of the season since 2001, as the Packers lost 31\u201317.<ref>{{cite web |title=NFL promptly defends latest roughing the passer flag against Clay Matthews III |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/24773771/nfl-promptly-defends-latest-roughing-passer-flag-clay-matthews |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=September 23, 2018|date=September 23, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAfter the conclusion of the 2018 season, Matthews became an [[Free agent#National Football League (NFL) usage|unrestricted free agent]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hodkiewicz |first1=Wes |title=Negotiation windows opens today for NFL free agents |url=https://www.packers.com/news/negotiation-windows-opens-today-for-nfl-free-agents |website=www.packers.com |accessdate=March 13, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190313161713/https://www.packers.com/news/negotiation-windows-opens-today-for-nfl-free-agents |archivedate=March 13, 2019 |date=March 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles Rams===\n====2019 season====\nOn March 19, 2019, Matthews signed a two-year contract with the [[Los Angeles Rams]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Rams, Clay Matthews agree to terms on two-year deal|url=https://www.therams.com/news/rams-clay-matthews-agree-to-terms-on-two-year-deal|author=Simmons, Myles|website=TheRams.com|date=March 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMatthews made his debut with the Rams in Week 1 against the [[2019 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]], making three tackles and sacking [[Cam Newton]] once as the Rams won 30\u201327.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127923 |title=Goff, Gurley lead Rams to 30-27 win over Panthers |date=September 8, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=September 8, 2019}}</ref> In Week 2 against the [[2019 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]], Matthews recorded another sack against [[Teddy Bridgewater]] as the Rams won 27\u20139.<ref>{{cite web |title=Brees injured, Rams beat Saints 27\u20139 in title game rematch |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128122 |website=ESPN |accessdate=September 17, 2019 |date=September 15, 2019}}</ref> In Week 3 against the [[2019 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], Matthews sacked [[Baker Mayfield]] twice in the 20\u201313 win.<ref>{{cite web |title=Goff throws 2 TDs passes, Rams hold off Browns 20-13 |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128125 |date=September 22, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=September 22, 2019}}</ref> In Week 5, after the Rams' 30\u201329 loss to the [[2019 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]], it was announced that Matthews suffered a broken jaw and would undergo surgery.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hart |first1=Torrey |title=Rams veteran Clay Matthews to miss extended time with broken jaw |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/rams-veteran-clay-matthews-to-miss-extended-time-with-broken-jaw-223453321.html |website=sports.yahoo.com |accessdate=October 11, 2019 |date=October 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Thiry |first1=Lindsey |title=Rams' Clay Matthews has broken jaw, out at least a month |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/27768760/rams-clay-matthews-suffers-broken-jaw-vs-seahawks-least-month |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=October 11, 2019 |date=October 4, 2019}}</ref> In the off-season, on March 19, 2020, Matthews was released by the Rams.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jackson |first1=Stu |title=Rams release OLB Clay Matthews |url=https://www.therams.com/news/rams-release-olb-clay-matthews |website=therams.com |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Thiry |first1=Lindsey |title=Rams release RB Todd Gurley, LB Clay Matthews |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/28927368/rams-release-rb-todd-gurley |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==NFL career statistics==\n===Regular season===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! colspan=\"2\"|Games !! colspan=\"4\"|Tackles !! colspan=\"6\"|Inte